{
  "text": "Single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) are widely used as molecular genetic markers in genetic linkage mapping [CITATION_1] , diversity analysis [CITATION_2] , cultivar identification [CITATION_3] , and marker-assisted selection (MAS) [CITATION_4] . Recent studies of the peach have shown that SNPs are distributed at a frequency of one SNP for every 598 bp, one indel for every 4189 bp; moreover, variability is ~6-fold higher in noncoding regions when compared to coding regions (one SNP for every 390 bp in noncoding DNA vs one for every 1850 bp in coding DNA) [CITATION_5] . Additionally, a 9K SNP array distributed over all 8 peach chromosomes, with an average spacing of 26.7 kb between SNPs, was recently developed [CITATION_6] , which can be used worldwide for genetic studies.",
